addr="jms-00NP"
title="The principle of well-founded induction">well-founded induction</fr:link></fr:title><fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>31</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
type="local"
href="marcelofiore.xml"
addr="marcelofiore"
title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The “strong” or “complete” induction principle for natural numbers states that for any subset <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S\subseteq  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\forall  x\in  \mathbb {N}\mathpunct {.} x\in  S]]></fr:tex> if and only if we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[0\in  S]]></fr:tex> and, for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m\in  S]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m<n]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in  S]]></fr:tex>. This is precisely the statement of <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00NP.xml"
addr="jms-00NP"
title="The principle of well-founded induction">well-founded induction</fr:link> for the <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00NM.xml"
addr="jms-00NM"
title="A well-founded relation on the naturals">strictly less-than relation</fr:link>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
